# 🏗 Step 1 — Slave: Store 2 Read Requests

Create small request buffer:

```verilog
reg        req_valid [0:1];
reg [1:0]  req_id    [0:1];
reg [31:0] req_addr  [0:1];
reg [7:0]  req_len   [0:1];
```

Add pointer:

```verilog
reg [0:0] write_ptr;
```

---

## Capture AR requests

```verilog
always @(posedge ACLK) begin
    if (!ARESETN) begin
        req_valid[0] <= 0;
        req_valid[1] <= 0;
    end
    else if (ARVALID && ARREADY) begin
        req_valid[write_ptr] <= 1;
        req_id[write_ptr]    <= ARID;
        req_addr[write_ptr]  <= ARADDR;
        req_len[write_ptr]   <= ARLEN;

        write_ptr <= write_ptr + 1;
    end
end
```

ARREADY should be 1 if any slot is free:

```verilog
assign ARREADY = !(req_valid[0] && req_valid[1]);
```

---

# 🧠 Step 2 — Choose Which Request to Serve

We create a selector:

```verilog
reg serve_index;
```

When idle:

```verilog
if (req_valid[0] && req_valid[1])
    serve_index <= $random % 2;   // choose randomly
else if (req_valid[0])
    serve_index <= 0;
else if (req_valid[1])
    serve_index <= 1;
```

This creates out-of-order behavior.

---

# 🏗 Step 3 — Start Read Burst From Selected Slot

Load working registers:

```verilog
current_id   <= req_id[serve_index];
current_addr <= req_addr[serve_index];
current_len  <= req_len[serve_index];

req_valid[serve_index] <= 0;
```

---

# 🏗 Step 4 — Send Data with RID

During data phase:

```verilog
RVALID <= 1;
RID    <= current_id;
RDATA  <= memory[current_addr];
```

Last beat:

```verilog
if (beat_count == current_len) begin
    RLAST <= 1;
end
```

Now responses may return:

```
RID=1 first
RID=0 later
```

This is legal AXI.

