# 🏗 Step 1 — Arbitration (Read Address Channel)

We check:

```verilog
if (M0_ARVALID)
    grant M0;
else if (M1_ARVALID)
    grant M1;
```

Simple priority.

---

# 🏗 Step 2 — Forward Signals

If M0 granted:

```verilog
S_ARVALID = M0_ARVALID;
S_ARADDR  = M0_ARADDR;
S_ARID    = M0_ARID;
```

If M1 granted:

```verilog
S_ARVALID = M1_ARVALID;
S_ARADDR  = M1_ARADDR;
S_ARID    = {1'b1, M1_ARID}; 
```

⚠ IMPORTANT

We modify ID to include master number.

Example:

```
MSB = master number
LSB = original ID
```

So slave can return response properly.

This is how real interconnects work.

---

# 🧠 Why Modify ID?

Because both masters might use ID=0.

Without modification:

```
M0 sends ID=0
M1 sends ID=0
```

Slave cannot distinguish.

So interconnect makes:

```
M0 ID=0 → 2'b00
M1 ID=0 → 2'b10
```

MSB = master select.

---

# 🏗 Step 3 — Route Read Data Back

When slave responds:

```verilog
if (S_RVALID) begin
    if (S_RID[1] == 0)
        route to M0
    else
        route to M1
end
```

And strip MSB before returning:

```verilog
M0_RID = S_RID[0];
M1_RID = S_RID[0];
```

---

# 🏗 Interconnect Read Address Logic (Simplified)

```verilog
always @(*) begin
    if (M0_ARVALID) begin
        grant = 0;
    end else if (M1_ARVALID) begin
        grant = 1;
    end
end

assign S_ARVALID = (grant == 0) ? M0_ARVALID : M1_ARVALID;
assign S_ARADDR  = (grant == 0) ? M0_ARADDR  : M1_ARADDR;
assign S_ARID    = (grant == 0) ? {1'b0, M0_ARID}
                                : {1'b1, M1_ARID};

assign M0_ARREADY = (grant == 0) ? S_ARREADY : 0;
assign M1_ARREADY = (grant == 1) ? S_ARREADY : 0;
```

---

# 🏗 Read Data Routing

```verilog
assign M0_RVALID = S_RVALID && (S_RID[1] == 0);
assign M1_RVALID = S_RVALID && (S_RID[1] == 1);

assign M0_RDATA  = S_RDATA;
assign M1_RDATA  = S_RDATA;

assign M0_RID    = S_RID[0];
assign M1_RID    = S_RID[0];

assign S_RREADY  = (S_RID[1] == 0) ? M0_RREADY : M1_RREADY;
```

